Disposition Summary

2024-02-29

Data Details and Insights

The following dataset contains information candidate’s Disposition Ratings. Students and educators are required to abide by the criteria, as well as understand concepts and practice while being rated by instructions in selected program classes.

Survey Questionnaire

The rubric consists of 8 questions with the possible answers being: Unacceptable, Developing, Proficient, Exemplary, and Not Observed. Answers without response will be marked as NA.

  • Social-Emotional and Cognitive Presence
    • Exemplary(4): Consistently demonstrates self-confidence/enthusiasm/positive demeanor; exceptional judgement and strong mindset.
    • Proficient(3): Generally demonstrates self-confidence/enthusiasm/positive demeanor; satisfactory judgement and mindset.
    • Developing(2): Inconsistently demonstrates self-confidence/enthusiasm/positive demeanor; nearing satisfactory judgement and mindset.
    • Unacceptable(1): Lacking in self-confidence/enthusiasm/positive demeanor; judgement and mindset need improving.
  • Compliance
    • Exemplary(4): Fully complies with and encourages school regulations; follows standards and has positive attitude about compliance.
    • Proficient(3): Complies with school regulations; follows standards and has general attitude about compliance.
    • Developing(2): Complies inconsistently with school regulations; inconsistent with following standards and lacking compliance.
    • Unacceptable(1): Rarely complies with school regulations; doesn’t follow standards and has negative attitude about compliance.
  • Communication
    • Exemplary(4): Consistently demonstrates confidentiality communication; successfully communicates with others.
    • Proficient(3): Understands need for confidentiality in communication; clearly communicates with others.
    • Developing(2): Inconsistently demonstrates confidentiality in communication; sometimes communicates with others.
    • Unacceptable(1): Inappropriately demonstrates confidentiality in communication; does not adequately communicate with others.
  • Ethical and Professional Behavior
    • Exemplary(4): Committed to the highest levels of integrity/honestly; uses exceptionally good judgement.
    • Proficient(3): Displays highest levels of integrity/honestly; uses solid good judgement.
    • Developing(2): Inconsistent levels of integrity/honestly; judgement not always solid.
    • Unacceptable(1): Lacking levels of integrity/honestly; does not exhibit good judgement.
  • Commitment to Individual Learners
    • Exemplary(4): Demonstrates belief that all students can learn; persistent and responsive when trying to meet needs of all students.
    • Proficient(3): Demonstrates belief that most students can learn; becoming responsive when trying to meet needs of all students.
    • Developing(2): Demonstrates inconsistent belief that students can learn; inconsistent when trying to meet needs of all students.
    • Unacceptable(1): Does not demonstrate belief that all students can learn; lacks persistence and responsiveness when trying to meet needs of all students.
  • Commitment to Improving Understanding
    • Exemplary(4): Seeks ways to improve content knowledge/teaching skills; accepts constructive criticism and willing to work on strengths/weaknesses.
    • Proficient(3): Understands need to improve content knowledge/teaching skills; listens to constructive criticism and makes effort to work on strengths/weaknesses.
    • Developing(2): Unaware of need to improve content knowledge/teaching skills; inconsistent in accepting constructive criticism and willingness to work on strengths/weaknesses.
    • Unacceptable(1): Disagrees with need to improve content knowledge/teaching skills; rarely listens to constructive criticism and lacks willingness to work on strengths/weaknesses.
  • Commitment to Teaching
    • Exemplary(4): Consistent and diligent in planning for instruction/assessment; consistently finds ways to improve student learning.
    • Proficient(3): Consistent in planning for instruction/assessment; finds ways to improve student learning.
    • Developing(2): Inconsistent in planning for instruction/assessment; inconsistent in finding ways to improve student learning.
    • Unacceptable(1): Rarely plans for instruction/assessment; doesn’t find ways to improve student learning.
  • Commitment to Profession and Collaboration
    • Exemplary(4): Collaborates with students/others to improve learner growth and development; embraces learning communities.
    • Proficient(3): Understands need to collaborate with students/others to improve learner growth and development; engages in learning communities.
    • Developing(2): Inconsistent with planning with students/others to improve learner growth and development; inconsistently engages in learning communities.
    • Unacceptable(1): Negative about collaboration with students/others to improve learner growth and development; does not engage in learning communities.

Tidying Process

The initial data consisted of various observations per student and their responses for each class taken. The answers provided corresponded with the rubric responses stated above.

First, NA values were set to a stated value of 2.5, followed by replacing string responses with digits ranging from 1-4. Newly updated scores were then added into a singular rating for each class taken. Once all scores were tallied up, the best score per student was then selected and put into the Disposition_Best_Score column. Lastly, to reduce the data, all responses were nested into Disposition_Scores, compressing all observation into one row per student.

Brief Look into the Updated Data

The following is a brief overview of the Disposition data set. A brief explanation on the variables:

  • StudentID: Unique identifier for each student surveyed.

  • Disposition_Scores: a list of composed of all responses to the survey by each student. It consists of Evaluator Code, Semester, Course, Questions 1-8, and the Best Score compiled by all responses.

  • Disposition_Best_Score: the highest Disposition score recorded from all courses taken by the questionnaire.

Current Data Overview

The table provides a glimpse at the updated dataset. Please note that the [object Object] are the nested results for all classes taken by the student.

datatable(disposition, class = 'cell-border stripe', rownames = FALSE, options = list(pageLength = 5))
new_disp <- disposition |> 
  unnest(Disposition_Scores)
View(new_disp)

Summary Findings

The following table showcases a brief summary into the class data:

  • Class and Code: classes provided.

  • Semesters_offered: count of semester where the classe was offered.

  • overall_avg_bestscore: the average best score for all students in that particular class.

  • best_score: highest score recorded in the class.

  • best_semester: semester with the highest score recorded in where the class was offered.

Data Visualization

The following graph contains the distribution of average disposition score per student, followed by the amounts of courses/classes taken per semester.

# Avg score per Semester
disp1 <-new_disp |> 
  group_by(Semester, Course) |> 
  arrange(Course) |> 
  summarise(total = n(),
            avg_best_score = round(mean(best_score, na.rm = TRUE), 2)) |> 
  mutate(Class = word(Course, 1),
         Code = str_extract(Course, "(\\d)+"))

# Avg score overall per class.
#panderOptions('table.split.table', Inf)
summary1 <- new_disp |> 
    mutate(Class = word(Course, 1),
         Code = str_extract(Course, "(\\d)+")) |> 
   group_by(Class, Code) |> 
   summarise(Students_Enrolled = n(),
             Semesters_Offered = length(unique(Semester)),
             Avg_Best_Score = round(mean(best_score, na.rm = TRUE),2 ),
            Best_Score_Recorded = round(max(best_score, na.rm = TRUE),2 ))

# Show a table summary.
datatable(summary1, class = 'cell-border stripe', rownames = FALSE, options = list(pageLength = 10))

The following summary contains information about the courses offered, students enrolled, semester, average disposition score per course, and the highest recorded score per class.

# Find avg score per student.
disp2 <- new_disp |> 
  group_by(StudentID) |> 
  summarise(avg_score = round(mean(best_score, na.rm = TRUE),2 ))
# Create histogram.
ggplot(disp2, aes(x = avg_score, y = after_stat(density)))+
  geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "#8a909c")+
  geom_density(color = "#3450ed", linewidth = 1, bw = 1)+
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=mean(avg_score, na.rm = TRUE)),
            color="red", linetype="solid", size=1)+
  labs(y = "Count",
       x = "Score",
       title = "Average Disposition Score per Student") +
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        legend.position = "none")

Disposition Scores by those with Education Majors

# Get the student information of those found in the full set using the avg disp score. 
new_test <- subset(df, (StudentID %in% disp2$StudentID))
View(new_test)
# Join sets.
new_test1 <- new_test |> 
  left_join(disp2, by = "StudentID")
# List of student with disp scores that did not transer over.
not_transfer <- subset(disp2, !(StudentID %in% df$StudentID)) #860

#-----------------------------
# Find those with education majors.
major_test <- new_test1 |> 
  mutate(school = case_when(
                           str_detect(BachDegreesEarned, "(?i)education|(?i)early | (?i)child ") ~ "education",
                           TRUE ~ "other")) |> 
  filter(school == "education")
# Find avg score per student for those with education majors.

# Create histogram.
ggplot(major_test, aes(x = avg_score, y = after_stat(density)))+
  geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "#c5c5c7")+
  geom_density(color = "red", linewidth = 1, bw = 1)+
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=mean(avg_score, na.rm = TRUE)),
            color="#3450ed", linetype="solid", size=1)+
  labs(y = "Count",
       x = "Score",
       title = "Average Disposition Score per Student",
       subtitle = "with Education Degrees") +
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        legend.position = "none")
